Evidence in page: 
Nikoloz (Niko) Muskhelishvili (... 16 February [O.S. 4 February] 1891 – 15 July 1976) was a Soviet Georgian mathematician, physicist and engineer who was one of the founders and first President (1941–1972) of the Georgian SSR Academy of Sciences... Muskhelishvili was born on 16 February 1891 in Tbilisi, then part of the Russian Empire into a family of engineers. He graduated from local grammar school in 1909 and afterwards from the Physics and Mathematics Faculty of Saint Petersburg in 1914. Immediately after his graduation he became head of Applied Mathematics of the same faculty... From 1917 to 1920 he worked as assistant director of the Petrograd University... Muskhelishvili conducted lessons in the Tbilisi State University and Polytechnic Institute as an assistant professor and from 1922 to 1938 as head professor... Muskhelishvili conducted fundamental research on the theories of physical elasticity, Integral equations, Boundary value problems and other... Highest regarded ones are the monographs "Some basic problems of the mathematical theory of elasticity" (1933) and "Singular Integral Equations" (1947)... He got also awarded for the launch of the world's first artificial satellite into space in 1961... Notable awards: Hero of Socialist Labour (1945), Stalin Prize (1941), (1947), Order of Lenin (1941), (1945), (1952), (1961), (1966), (1975), Lomonosov Gold Medal (1972).

Summary: 
Nikoloz Muskhelishvili (1891–1976) was a prominent Soviet Georgian mathematician, physicist, and engineer. He was a founder and the first President of the Georgian SSR Academy of Sciences (1941–1972). He studied and worked at Saint Petersburg University before moving to Tbilisi State University. His key scientific contributions were in the theories of physical elasticity, integral equations, and boundary value problems, with highly regarded monographs published in 1933 and 1947. He also contributed to military research during WWII and the development of the world's first space satellite. He received numerous prestigious awards, including the Hero of Socialist Labour, the Stalin Prize, the Order of Lenin, and the Lomonosov Gold Medal. This comprehensive profile can be used to cross-reference against any specific clues.
