Evidence in page: 
Arnaud Beauville (born 10 May 1947) is a French mathematician, whose research interest is algebraic geometry.
Beauville earned his doctorate from Paris Diderot University in 1977, with a thesis regarding Prym varieties and the Schottky problem, under supervision of Jean-Louis Verdier.
He has been a professor at the Université Paris-Sud, then Director of the Mathematics Department at the École Normale Supérieure. He is currently Professor emeritus at the Université de Nice Sophia-Antipolis.
Beauville was a visiting scholar at the Institute for Advanced Study in the summer of 1982. He was an invited speaker at the International Congress of Mathematicians in 1986 at Berkeley. He was a member of Bourbaki. He has had 25 Ph.D. students, among them Claire Voisin, Olivier Debarre, Yves Laszlo.
In 2012 he became a fellow of the American Mathematical Society.

Summary: 
Arnaud Beauville (born May 10, 1947) is a prominent French mathematician known for his work in algebraic geometry. He completed his doctorate at Paris Diderot University in 1977 under the supervision of Jean-Louis Verdier. Throughout his career, he has held significant academic positions, including Professor at Université Paris-Sud and Director of the Mathematics Department at the École Normale Supérieure, and currently serves as Professor emeritus at Université de Nice Sophia-Antipolis. Beauville has mentored 25 Ph.D. students, including notable mathematicians like Claire Voisin, Olivier Debarre, and Yves Laszlo. He has also been a visiting scholar at the Institute for Advanced Study, a member of the Bourbaki group, an invited speaker at the 1986 International Congress of Mathematicians, and became a fellow of the American Mathematical Society in 2012.
